iving in the United States, Europe, and Australia? Can we keep them out? Should we even be trying? Combining compelling firsthand reporting from around the world, incisive socioeconomic analysis, and a broad understanding of what's at stake politically and culturally, Immigrants is a passionate but lucid book. In our open world, more people will inevitably move across borders, Legrain says--and we should generally welcome them. They do the jobs we can't or won't do--and their diversity enriches us all. Left and Right, free marketeers and campaigners for global justice, enlightened patriots--all should rally behind the cause of freer migration, because They need Us and We need Them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aEmigration and immigrationvEconomic aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationvSocial aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationxEconomic aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationxSocial aspects. 0aEmigration and immigration. 0aImmigrantsvÉtats-Unis. 0aImmigrantszUnited States. 0aUnited StatesvEmigration and immigration. 0aÉmigration et immigrationvAspect social. 0aÉmigration et immigrationvAspect économique. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic Conditions.2bisacsh  aAffirmative action.  aAmericans.  aAsylum seeker.  aAustralia.  aAustralians.  aBlack market.  aBorder control.  aBritish people.  aBureaucrat.  aCanada.  aCanadians.  aCapitalism.  aCitizenship.  aCompetition.  aConsumption (economics).  aCountry of origin.  aCultural diversity.  aDeveloped country.  aEconomic growth.  aEconomist.  aEconomy.  aEmigration.  aEmployment.  aEntrepreneurship.  aEurope.  aFilipinos.  aForeign worker.  aGlobalization.  aHarvard University.  aHigh tech.  aHonduras.  aHousehold.  aHuman capital flight.  aIllegal immigration.  aImmigration p